A4.text: The House of Commons is the most powerful of the components of Parliament, particularly due to its sole right to determine taxation and the supply of money to the government.

A5.text: The Speaker's place may be taken by the Chairman of Ways and Means, the First Deputy Chairman, or the Second Deputy Chairman.

A6.text: Joint sessions are traditionally presided over by the speaker of the House.

A7.text: The Constitution requires the vice president (as president of the Senate) to preside over the counting of electoral votes by Congress.

A8.text: The president of the Federal Senate presides over the Board of the National Congress in the joint sessions of both houses.
